<div id="attachment_10720" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/2015/12/the-brewery-that-conquered-the-world/screen-shot-2015-12-27-at-11-48-12-am/" rel="attachment wp-att-10720"><img class="wp-image-10720" src="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.12-AM-1024x680.png" alt="Archive Manager expressing passionately how she may be forced to whip your ass for touching these items" width="600" height="398" srcset="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.12-AM-300x199.png 300w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.12-AM-768x510.png 768w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.12-AM-1024x680.png 1024w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.12-AM-226x150.png 226w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.12-AM.png 1098w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Archive Manager expressing passionately how she may be forced to whip your ass for touching these items.</p></div>
<div id="attachment_10721" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/2015/12/the-brewery-that-conquered-the-world/screen-shot-2015-12-27-at-11-48-40-am/" rel="attachment wp-att-10721"><img class="wp-image-10721" src="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.40-AM.png" alt="The brewery book of Sir Arthur Guinness from 1801" width="600" height="560" srcset="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.40-AM-300x280.png 300w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.40-AM-768x717.png 768w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.40-AM-161x150.png 161w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.40-AM-150x140.png 150w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-11.48.40-AM.png 783w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">The brewery book of Sir Arthur Guinness from 1801</p></div>
<div id="attachment_10727" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/2015/12/the-brewery-that-conquered-the-world/img_3527/" rel="attachment wp-att-10727"><img class="wp-image-10727" src="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMG_3527-768x1024.jpg" alt="message in a bottle sent from Dublin recovered in New Zealand" width="600" height="800" srcset="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMG_3527-225x300.jpg 225w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMG_3527-768x1024.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">message in a bottle sent from Dublin recovered in New Zealand</p></div>
<p>Before producing the stout that would make them the top brewery in the world by volume (until 1929), Guinness’ flagship was a Red Ale. It wasn’t until Arthur’s post collegiate trips to London that he was inspired to create an Irish version of the Porter.  Eighteenth century England is where Arthur fell in love with this style, a beer named for the dock workers who consumed it after their shift.</p>
<p>The nitro version of the Guinness that we know and love was introduced for the brewery’s 200<sup>th</sup> anniversary. Since then over 20 different styles have been created worldwide including exclusive varietals in countries like Belgium. On the top floor of the Storehouse is the Gravity Bar, an observation deck with a stunning view of Dublin and the Wicklow Mountains (the brewery’s water source). This is easily the busiest floor at Ireland’s most visited attraction. Everyone from Tom Cruise to President Obama to the Queen of England make it a point to visit Gravity Bar and enjoy a perfect pint. But the jewel of the facility is The Connoisseur Bar Experience &#8211; a private space that offers a deep dive into the full lineup of Guinness variants.</p>
<div id="attachment_10729" style="width: 1010px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/2015/12/the-brewery-that-conquered-the-world/dsc_0081-2/" rel="attachment wp-att-10729"><img class="wp-image-10729 size-full" src="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/DSC_0081-1.jpg" alt="Sir Hugh Beaver introducted Guinness Draught on nitro as part of the brewery's 200th anniversary" width="1000" height="664" srcset="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/DSC_0081-1-300x199.jpg 300w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/DSC_0081-1-768x510.jpg 768w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/DSC_0081-1-226x150.jpg 226w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/DSC_0081-1.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Sir Hugh Beaver and crew introduced Guinness Draught on nitro as part of the brewery&#8217;s 200th anniversary</p></div>
<div id="attachment_10731" style="width: 1010px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/2015/12/the-brewery-that-conquered-the-world/connie/" rel="attachment wp-att-10731"><img class="size-full wp-image-10731" src="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/connie.jpeg" alt="The Connoisseur Bar Experience" width="1000" height="750" srcset="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/connie-300x225.jpeg 300w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/connie-768x576.jpeg 768w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/connie-200x150.jpeg 200w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/connie.jpeg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">The Connoisseur Bar Experience</p></div>
<p><strong>Dublin Porter </strong>&#8211; 3.8% Created from brewers recipe logs from 1796. notes of dark chocolate, caramel and candied walnut.</p>
<p><strong>Guinness Extra Stout </strong>-5% A pale ale base to which is added the unfermented but hopped Guinness wort extract. By 1959 it became the number one selling beer worldwide for the brewery, surpassed by Guinness Draft in1961 . For years Moosehead Brewery in Canada made Extra Stout. The beer currently represents 40% of the company’s sales.</p>
<p><strong>Foreign Extra Stout</strong> -7.5% Started in 1821 as Extra Superior Stout. Developed for global export from Ireland, brewed with a generous amount of extra hops.</p>
<p><strong>West Indies Porter &#8211;</strong> 6% First brewed in 1801, both West Indies Porter and Dublin Porter saw a relaunch in 2014. As the name implies this beer was crafted with a higher gravity to maintain freshness for voyages to the Caribbean. West Indies Porter is the beer that went on to become Foreign Extra Stout.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/2015/12/the-brewery-that-conquered-the-world/screen-shot-2015-12-27-at-4-35-31-am/" rel="attachment wp-att-10712"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-10712" src="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-4.35.31-AM-1024x500.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-12-27 at 4.35.31 AM" width="900" height="439" srcset="http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-4.35.31-AM-768x375.png 768w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-4.35.31-AM-1024x500.png 1024w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-4.35.31-AM-250x122.png 250w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-4.35.31-AM-150x73.png 150w, http://www.chicagobeergeeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-27-at-4.35.31-AM.png 1099w" sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></a></p>
<p>To my surprise Nigeria drinks more Guinness than Ireland does. Three of the five official Guinness breweries reside in Africa – Nigeria, Ghana and Cameroon. The total outposts on this continent jumps to 20 when you include locations officially licensed to brew Guinness&#8230;and thats all just in Africa. Over 50 breweries worldwide currently produce the stout.</p>
<p>Guinness creates an experience that blends the power of history with irresistible storytelling. The result separates it from breweries with comparable size and reach. The world of advertising here is nothing short of brilliant. The ‘Guinness Is Good For You’ slogan ran for 40 years as doctors highlighted it’s medicinal properties. Everyone from nursing mothers to blood donors were encourage to enjoy a pint because of the high iron content.</p>
<p>John Gilroy, the English illustrator known for his Guinness ad posters created a zoo animal series that became nearly as identifiable as the harp on the beer labels.</p>
<p>As print ads gave way to TV, agencies associated with the brand continued to evolve their approach to include sophisticated pieces that captured every walk of life enjoying a Guinness.</p>
<p>This  global community has kept the company thriving 256 years after it was founded.</p>
